fields.name: Tesla Model 3
fields.description:
If youΓÇÖre looking for an affordable electric family car, the Tesla Model 3 should be right at the top of your shopping list. It was given a major update in late 2023 which gave it a sleeker, more aggressive exterior design and a subtly changed interior ΓÇô but perhaps more important is that updates make it more quiet and refined inside as well as more comfortable over bumps. It's so impressive that it has won the Outstanding EV Award at the 2024 Carwow Car of the Year Awards.

You can't overstate just how influential the Tesla Model 3 has been. Remember in the early-mid 2000s, when phone handsets were getting ever smaller and discreet ΓÇö until the chunky iPhone came along in 2007 to completely turn the industry on its head? Well, thatΓÇÖs sort of what the Model 3 has achieved with the car. Not only has Elon MuskΓÇÖs brainchild shown the world that long-range electric cars are today and not just the future, but in the process it also paved the way for alternatives such as the Polestar 2, Hyundai Ioniq 6, Kia EV6 and BYD Seal.

If there was one criticism you could levy at the old Model 3, it was that it had rather gawky styling, but the revised version has sharper, slimmer headlights that give it a more aggressive look. At the rear you get C-shaped lights that create a classier, more defined look than before.

There are changes under the metal, too. Tesla has always pushed the boundaries in terms of range, and now you can go even further between charges. The all-wheel drive Long Range model has an estimated range of 421 miles with the 18-inch wheels, though that drops by over 30 miles if you pick the 19-inch wheels. Even the standard rear-wheel drive version can go comfortably over 300 miles, plus you get access to Tesla's excellent Supercharger network.

fields.name: Volkswagen Passat
fields.description:
The Volkswagen Passat is back, and this time thereΓÇÖs no saloon option ΓÇô you can only get it as a mega spacious estate. ThatΓÇÖs no problem, though, because the Passat has always stood out for being big, practical and not quite as expensive as the Audi A4 Avant, BMW 3 Series Touring and Mercedes C-Class Estate.

ItΓÇÖs a bit like buying designer gear from TK Maxx ΓÇô youΓÇÖre getting the same sort of quality as you would from a big name store, but you donΓÇÖt feel quite as posh in the process.

Not that the Passat looks like a cheap alternative. ItΓÇÖs always had an understated class, and that continues with the latest model ΓÇô itΓÇÖs perhaps not as elegant as its predecessor but itΓÇÖs certainly smart enough. And if you go for the R-Line model you get a big, imposing grille up front to go with the smart full-width rear light bar thatΓÇÖs standard across the range.

ItΓÇÖs inside where Volkswagen has really taken the Passat up a notch, though. ThereΓÇÖs a massive infotainment display in the centre of the dashboard that runs VolkswagenΓÇÖs latest software. ItΓÇÖs a big improvement on recent VW systems, even if it is a touch annoying having to do everything through the screen.

Running behind this and into the digital instrument display is an illuminated panel that gives the Passat a cool modern look, particularly at night.

fields.name: BMW 320i
fields.description:
If you havenΓÇÖt heard of the BMW 3 Series, you havenΓÇÖt been paying attention. Simply put, itΓÇÖs one of the best all-rounders you can buy. If you are after a premium, practical family saloon and you love to drive, this is the car for you.

Like shopping at Waitrose instead of Lidl, or having Jamaican Blue Mountain coffee instead of Nescafe, itΓÇÖs about paying a little extra for a much higher quality product.

Clearly the 3 Series has some tough competition from the Mercedes C-Class, Audi A4, and even Alfa Romeo Giulia. But to cut a long story short, itΓÇÖs the best car in the segment, and an award-winner too ΓÇö the BMW 330e picked up the Best Family Hybrid Car in the 2021 carwow Car of the Year Awards, although since then Mercedes has launched the exceptionally talented new C300e plug-in hybridΓÇª

ItΓÇÖs arguably not the most handsome car in the class, as the styling is a bit overdone and fussy in places. But itΓÇÖs undeniably appealing, especially in the more muscular M Sport form, which comes with a sporty bodykit. The recent update has tidied things up slightly, and for the most part itΓÇÖs still a decent-looking car.

An update in 2023 introduced the big, curved digital screen first seen in the iX electric SUV, and more recently in the i4 electric four-door coupe. ItΓÇÖs a dramatic looking thing, and while BMW was at it, the centre console and switches were updated too.

fields.name: Audi A3 Sportback
fields.description:
Lamborghini-inspired design, super-advanced tech, and a luxury interior ΓÇô the big guns have definitely been rolled out to tempt you into the new premium hatchback Audi A3.

Its traditional alternatives are fellow posh Germans the BMW 1 Series and Mercedes A-Class, but the A3 actually shares plenty of parts with the new VW Golf, SEAT Leon and Skoda Octavia. As a result, these brandsΓÇÖ family hatchbacks are a bit like four children who all turned out very differently.

If the Skoda Octavia is the sensible one, the Seat Leon the sporty one and the Volkswagen Golf the easiest to get on with, the Audi A3 is the one who took a job in the city, likes expensive clothes and has a designer watch on the wrist. But itΓÇÖs not all show and no go. The Audi A3 is so good, it won Best Family Car in the 2021 carwow Car of the Year Awards.

In fact, the new A3 comes with the sportiest Audi interior youΓÇÖll see this side of the R8 supercar. It looks striking, and has been inspired by the one in the Lamborghini Urus, but while it feels decent for the most part, some of the materials donΓÇÖt quite feel supercar-posh in places.

It comes across as decently upmarket if you go for a high-spec model with the larger widescreen digital driverΓÇÖs display and built-in sat-nav. Thankfully, itΓÇÖs all dead easy to use and even entry-level cars get a cool 10-inch touchscreen and all the smartphone mirroring features you could want as standard.

fields.name: Renault Clio
fields.description:
If youΓÇÖre looking for an affordable city car, but donΓÇÖt want to sacrifice on style and practicality, the Renault Clio is an excellent option. It looks great inside and out and has a bigger boot than any of its small hatchback alternatives ΓÇô so itΓÇÖs good looking and practical, like a supermodel wearing cargo pants.

And a little nip and tuck for 2023 means it looks better than ever, with similar chic appeal to the Peugeot 208, making the pair stand out from the likes of the Ford Fiesta, Volkswagen Polo and Vauxhall Corsa.

ItΓÇÖs up front where itΓÇÖs really eye-catching now, with slim headlights and funky vertical daytime running lights flanking a new grille and prominent Renault logo. Round the back the new look is less obvious, but a tweaked bumper helps make the Clio look much more interesting.

ItΓÇÖs a similar story inside, with the profile-orientated infotainment display (on top-spec models) and new climate control buttons giving off a more premium feel than before. And while some scratchy plastics lower in the cabin betray the carΓÇÖs price, there are plenty of soft surfaces that are suitably upmarket.

For a small car, itΓÇÖs not at all cramped in the front, but those in the back will struggle for kneeroom in particular. Storage is fine wherever you sit, but youΓÇÖll want to leave most things in the cavernous boot ΓÇô at 391 litres itΓÇÖs more spacious than any alternatives' boots.

fields.name: Skoda Fabia
fields.description:
The Skoda Fabia is a small hatchback that shares its mechanical bits with the Volkswagen Polo and Seat Ibiza, but it has always been the most sensible option of the trio. ItΓÇÖs the most practical and usually the cheapest, but has never been the most exciting or upmarket version.

That direction has been continued here on the design front, with the new Fabia featuring SkodaΓÇÖs recognisable Ned Flanders moustache-like grille, simple but effective creases and smart alloy wheels ΓÇô nothing to set the heart ablaze, but completely inoffensive.

Inside itΓÇÖs a similar story. ItΓÇÖs been smartened up compared to its predecessor, but itΓÇÖs relatively simple. Dashes of colour, a large enough infotainment screen and enough space help this cabin do the job, but youΓÇÖll find a fair amount of scratchy plastics.

YouΓÇÖll be able to get comfortable very quickly though, as the Fabia has plenty of adjustment so you can find the right position. Add to that the comfort seats, which are excellent on longer journeys, and youΓÇÖve got an interior that definitely ranks function over form.

Passengers will also be pretty happy as rear space is good. ThereΓÇÖs plenty of head and legroom, while thereΓÇÖs easy access to ISOFIX points for child seats.

The FabiaΓÇÖs boot is also very practical. This class-leading one has 380 litres on hand, which is very impressive for a car of this size. It beats the Volkswagen Polo by around 30 litres, but it smashes the Ford Fiesta by almost 90 litres. ThatΓÇÖs extended to 1,190 litres when folding the rear seats down ΓÇô but youΓÇÖll need to buy the optional variable boot floor for a flat space.

fields.name: Audi A4
fields.description:
The Audi A4 is to modern-day business transport what the Ford Cortina was back in the 1970s. Basically, if your daily attire involves a shirt and tie, the Audi A4 is likely to be quite high on your shopping list, doubtless alongside the BMW 3 Series, Jaguar XE and Mercedes C-Class. This is thanks ΓÇô in part ΓÇô to its sharp style, classy interior and economical petrol and diesel engines.

The Audi A4 has a few sporty styling tweaks to help it stand out from these cars, however, so has plenty of aggressive intakes, sharply creased lines and ΓÇô depending on which model you pick ΓÇô some seriously bright Matrix LED headlights. If the old A4 was frowning, this new one is clenching its teeth and staring right through you.

Inside, the changes arenΓÇÖt quite so in-your-face, but you do get a whopping-great 10-inch infotainment display as standard with all the navigation and smartphone-mirroring mod-cons you could ask for.

fields.name: Skoda Octavia
fields.description:
Skoda often swoops in and obliterates its Volkswagen Group stablemates VW, SEAT and Audi on space and practicality, and the Skoda Octavia is one of the best examples of that. ItΓÇÖs a family car thatΓÇÖs bigger than a Volkswagen Golf, Seat Leon, Mercedes A-Class, Audi A3 or BMW 1 Series, but costs less to buy.

This Skoda Octavia might be all-new, but itΓÇÖs still very clearly an Octavia. Up front, you get the same distinctive grille, though itΓÇÖs bluffer than before and the horrible twin headlights of the old car have been scrapped for a pair of slim-line LEDs.

The crease that runs down the side of the car makes it look more imposing ΓÇô like shoulder pads in a 1980s suit jacket ΓÇô and you can have wheels up to 19 inches in size, even on non-vRS models. The new look is finished off with crystal-style rear LEDs.

Skoda has made a big effort to make the new Octavia feel more upmarket than the last car, with soft-touch plastics, textile padded trim finishes and thickly stuffed seats that could rival your armchair at home for comfort. Even so, itΓÇÖs still blander inside than a Focus or Leon.

That said, thereΓÇÖs an exception. The interior is dominated by a large central infotainment touchscreen, even on entry-level models, while the majority of physical buttons are found right in the centre of the dash. It looks modern and is easy to use, with Apple CarPlay and Android Auto standard. Lovely digital driverΓÇÖs dials come included too.

fields.name: Tesla Model Y
fields.description:
The Tesla Model Y is an electric SUV that offers great value for money with cutting edge technology, loads of range from its big battery versions, and impressive practicality.

ItΓÇÖs based on the Model 3, but itΓÇÖs a bit bigger and taller. ItΓÇÖs like going for the Xbox Series X over the Series S ΓÇô itΓÇÖs very similar under the skin, but you just get a little bit more of everything.

And if youΓÇÖre shopping for the Model Y there are countless similarly priced electric alternatives to consider, such as the Audi Q4 e-tron, Kia EV6 and Ford Mustang Mach-e ΓÇô even the slightly less practical but more affordable Tesla Model 3.

ThereΓÇÖs a lot to love about the Tesla Model Y, but one of those things is not its exterior design. ItΓÇÖs a rather anonymous blob, particularly with its lack of a traditional grille up front, and the odd sloping roof thatΓÇÖs probably meant to ape sporty coupe lines but instead just gives the car really bizarre proportions.

fields.name: Hyundai Ioniq 5
fields.description:
The Hyundai Ioniq 5 is one of the most striking-looking electric cars out there, but it is more than just squared-off lines and sharp angles ΓÇô itΓÇÖs out to take on the likes of the Volkswagen ID4 and Ford Mustang Mach-e.

Those ΓÇÿlate ΓÇÿ80s videogameΓÇÖ looks create a trick of the eye. The Ioniq 5 hides its size well, as it actually has the dimensions of a family SUV, which means you get loads of room inside for people and luggage alike.

Those futuristic looks arenΓÇÖt restricted to the outside, either, with the interior continuing the stylish minimalist theme. There are two large, high-res screens up on the dash and a load of really nice feeling materials dotted around. Sure, some arenΓÇÖt quite up to the same standard ΓÇô the odd button here and there and the ΓÇÿgearΓÇÖ selector up by the side of the steering wheel to mention a couple ΓÇô but the overall feeling is that this is a really posh cabin.

ItΓÇÖs certainly not all style and no substance, though, as the driving position is great (a little more wheel adjustment could be nice though) and there is loads of space for taller passengers in the second row.

fields.content: I absolutely love my Tesla Model Y! The sleek design, spacious interior, and incredible performance make it the perfect choice for anyone looking to go electric. It's so smooth to drive, and the autopilot features are a game-changer. Plus, knowing I'm driving emission-free gives me peace of mind. Tesla really hit it out of the park with the Model Y

I think the Tesla Model 3 is amazing. It looks great, has cool technology, and can go far on a single charge. The inside is simple and modern, with a big touchscreen that's easy to use. The autopilot and safety features make driving safer and more relaxed. No wonder so many people love it!

As a daily user, I'm not impressed with the Tesla Model 3. The interior feels too plain and the touchscreen controls can be distracting while driving. The build quality could be better, and I've heard about reliability issues. For the price, I expected more.
